..TEXT:
|Qual si partio~... |noverca~: Hippolytus was a
son of Theseus by Hippolyte, a queen of the Amazons.  Theseus
later married Phaedra, who fell in love with her stepson
Hippolytus; on his rejecting her shameful proposals, she accused
him to his father of having attempted her dishonor.  Theseus
thereupon cursed his son, who was obliged to flee from Athens.
He subsequently met his death in fulfillment of his father's
curse.  When Theseus afterwards discovered that Phaedra's
accusation was false, Phaedra killed herself in despair.  Dante
got the story of Hippolytus and Phaedra from Ovid (^Metam.~ XV,
497-505).  See Virgil, ^Aen.~ VII, 761-782; Cicero, ^De
officiis~, I, x, 32.  |noverca~ = ^matrigna~, "stepmother."  Cf.
^Par.~ XVI, 59.
