..TEXT:
|notabili fier l'opere sue~: Can Grande's great deeds
were martial, evidence of the fact that he was chiefly
influenced, at birth, by the planet Mars.  The following is a
summary of the most important events in his career:
..TEXT:
1308-1311. Joint lord of Verona with Alboino.
..TEXT:
1311. Imperial vicar in Verona (Villani, IX, 20); November, sole
lord of Verona; December, rescued Brescia from the Guelphs
(Villani, IX, 32); helped to take Vicenza from the Paduans.
..TEXT:
1312. Imperial vicar in Vicenza.
..TEXT:
1314. September, repelled Paduan attack on Vicenza (Villani, IX,
63); October, made peace with Padua and was confirmed in lordship
of Vicenza.
..TEXT:
1315. Attacked Cremona, Parma, and Reggio, in alliance with
Passerino Bonaccolsi, lord of Mantua and Modena.
..TEXT:
1316. Dante perhaps at Verona.
..TEXT:
1317. May, with help of Uguccione della Faggiuola repelled fresh
attack of Paduans on Vicenza; December, appointed imperial vicar
in Verona and Vicenza by Frederick of Austria; besieged Padua
(Villani, IX, 89).
..TEXT:
1318. April, took Cremona (Villani, IX, 91); December 16, elected
captain general of Ghibelline league in Lombardy at Soncino.
..TEXT:
1319. August, besieged Padua (Villani, IX, 100).
..TEXT:
1320. August 25, repulsed by Paduans, Uguccione della Faggiuola
being killed (Villani, IX, 121).
..TEXT:
1322. September, took part with Passerino Bonaccolsi in siege of
Reggio (Villani, IX, 167).
..TEXT:
1324. June, attacked in Padua by German forces of Otto of
Austria, whom he repelled (Villani, IX, 255).
..TEXT:
1327. Besieged Padua (Villani, X, 42).
..TEXT:
1328. Captured Mantua; September 8, at invitation of Paduan
Ghibellines became lord of Padua (Villani, X, 101).
..TEXT:
1329. July 18, took Treviso, where he died (July 22); buried at
Verona (Villani, X, 137).
..TEXT:
|fier~ = ^saranno.~
..TCHR:
1676
..AUTH:
